questionTemplates.text:
W: Jason worked as a secretary for three years. Then he became a newspaperman. After that he started writing novels.
M: I know. And he has been doing nothing else ever since.
{a}

M: Pardon me. I asked for filet mignon.
W: I'm sorry. I'll see that it's changed.
{a}

W: Why don't you go to bed?
M: I have to finish this homework first.
{a}

W: Dad, I can't find my magazines. Have you seen them?
M: Oh, yes, they are on your desk.
{a}

W: My mother sits in front of the TV for hours every evening.
M: Well, TV has that effect on a lot of people. It takes people away from reading, talking and walking.
{a}

W: We heard that when you are a kid, you submitted a story to Reader's Digest.
M: Well, I don't remember this story exactly, but my idea of a great time then was a pad of lined paper and a new blue pen. I thought myself as a Reader's Digest member at the age of six.
{a}

W: May I help you?
M: Yes, I'd like to try on some sports jackets. I prefer something like the one I'm wearing.
{a}

W: Peter, how is the weather now? Is it still raining?
M: No, but there's still lots of clouds. The weatherman said the sun wouldn't come out until next week.
{a}

M: You haven't got the date fixed for the job interview yet, have you?
W: There is a long waiting list, I have to wait until my name gets to the top.
{a}

M: Hello, may I speak to Andrew, please?
W: Oh, hold on a second, I'll check for you.
{a}

W: I hope you like the book I lent you. I wasn't sure if you'd be interested.
M: I had the same doubt at first. But once I started, I simply couldn't put it down.
{a}

M: Are you really leaving for Hongkong tomorrow morning?
W: Yeah, I guess so. I got the air tickets. I can't wait to see Bill there.
{a}

W: Hi, Li Hua. How is everything?
M: Not bad, except for my toothache.
{a}

F: Hurry, it's 9 o'clock.
M: You forgot. Our clock is 20 minutes quick!
{a}

M: If it rains, we can't go out to the park tomorrow.
F: Don't worry, I think it won't.
{a}

M: Of the two houses we have seen, which one do you think fits our needs better, the first one or the second one?
W: The second one. It seems very expensive. But in the long run, it will save up the money on the maintenance.
{a}

F: Mary is becoming rather worried about her mother's health.
M: Yes...me too.
{a}

A: Morning, Keven!
K: Morning, Adams. Would you like to have a look at this watch? It doesn't keep good time.
{a}

M: My radio doesn't work. What do you think I should do?
W: Why not call Mr. White?
{a}

M: What would you like for dessert? I think I'll have apple pie and ice cream.
W: The chocolate cake looks great, but I have to watch my weight. You go ahead and get yours.
{a}

M: How did your parents like the play?
W: My mother thought the language was terrible, but my father liked it.
{a}

M: I feel so stressed out right now! Work has been crazy lately. I need to relax.
W: Just sit down, and I'll get you a Coke and a sandwich, OK?
{a}

M: Shall we go to the company picnic?
W: I'd like to, but I really can't make it on August 6th.
{a}

W: Both Sally and Windy live on the 16th floor. Am I right?
M: No. Sally lives on the 15th floor, while Windy and I live on the 16th floor.
{a}

W: Do you want to show me your new book?
M: I will show you next week.
{a}

M: So strange, I was cut off in the middle of the conversation. I called the operator, but no one answered.
W: You may try again.
{a}

W: I'm awfully sorry, but I've knocked over that display of bowls over there.
M: Oh, dear! Well, it's all right, madam. We'll see to it.
{a}
